I am British; I live in a society that is broadly fair, uses law appropriately, cares for its citizens and residents, is curious about the world and wants the whole world to be a better place.

Make your customer support agents look like gods in the eyes of your customers; make sure they have all the resources, knowledge and connections required to efficiently figure things out and have things fixed even if they can't do it themselves.
(3/3) Integrate the support team with your product teams. Good agents know the product in and out; every new feature, bugs that are currently being fixed and who's working on what.
Your agents should be able to fix things for the customer instead of telling them how to fix it themselves. Customers need to feel like they're talking to someone who can actually fix their problems.

(2/3) Empower your support team with the right tools and access. If all your support team does is dig up a link from a knowledge base and send it to the customer, you're really not doing much more than a self-serve help-desk.

Two, the rest of your team can easily get tagged on and jump into issues that need a little extra work. Three, and most important, it makes for a seamless experience when it comes to the customers. They can reach you anywhere and expect to get the same level of support.

(1/3) Pay for a good help-desk software and manage all your tickets on there. One, it consolidates your support requests; customer support agents can track the tickets they're working on across all platforms from one place.

JH: Remaining challenge 5: Move from single copy refinement to heterogeneous ensembles. Use replica simulations with SAXS data. SAXS data can remove some FF uncertainty. Related to ideas from @CarloCamilloni @BonomiMax and others. 7/

JH: You can fool yourself by making too strong assumptions about what you know. You may get tiny errors of ensembles if you fit the weights assuming you know the states. If you fit states and weights at the same time it becomes more realistic 6/

JH: At the same time Bayesian methods solve Remaining challenge 3 (How weigh data against force fields), challenge 4 (Random errors in experiments are getting small and we need to worry systematic errors) 5/

JH: Remaining challenge 2: We cannot really give confidence intervals of fitted structural models. Bayesian methods to the rescue. Apply inferential structure determination to SAXS and integrate out nuisance parameters. 4/ https://t.co/9rBVYhxVjL

JH: Remaining challenge 1: Often you cannot cross validate SAXS analyses with SAXS (Rfree-like) because you cannot easily decompose data into an independent dataset. One solution is to cross validate against SANS data. 3/
JH: Forward model WAXSIS (https://t.co/ockFCVVFfU) based on older work (https://t.co/6oTlsFql0R) uses physical model for solvation layer and dynamics 2/

JH: To extract info from SAXS we need three ingredients: 1: A physical model (FF), 2: a foward model (calculate SAXS from structures) and 3: a sampling algorithm (eg Bayesian/Maximum Entropy). We generally use expensive but accurate methods 1/

Even more beautiful is the co-localization of these regulatory regions in the nucleus. Trans-eQTL that are difficult to detect, can now be tested; discovering 27 new trans QTLs. Model is quite complex, but it's reality and new models are more informative.
In simple words, interaction and regulation changes depending on the genetic differences. The positioning of the CRD is important to make it causal or not. Position in the genome does matter.

3 types of correlation depending on level of itneraction (often 3D is not correlated to c-QTL data). These CRDs are smalled than TADs, are "sub-TADS". Genetics brought into these CRDs: assign to genes (12K of the CRDs); QTLs (>6K) are activity CRDs; and 110 structure-CRDs-QTL.

This is a wonderful story how a Nation can re-organize the health system and in the long term SAVE money. It seems an obvious, but this does not happen easily if you do not have a long history?

From 100K to 5M genomes (details ongoing).Pilot 100K/year; Longitudinal life course follow up.-Can do AI for research AND for diagnosis. Data scattered around providers (needs to unify in same infrastructure). Important: 50% gender balance among leaders of the project!

Company can analyze but never take out. TB addressed. Education: profound impact, including university courses.New genome medicine services (national level operation); organization shared by NHS and Genomics England (complex pattern).Pharmacogenomics: another important aspect.

Cancer patients history: can follow trajectories (from long term to recently only treated patients). Many improvements possible of course; both in reading and bioinformatics. tools today are OK, enough for diagnostics, but still room to improve.

(24) I'd like to thank my advisor, Richard Michelmore, all of my lab mates (especially @RJuGil, @KIGFletcher, and @Herculien), @GittaCoaker and Ian Korf, my undergrads, and my friends & family for supporting me on this project and during grad school in general. El fin. ‚ò∫Ô∏è

(23) In high school, I became interested in genetics learning about the human genome. It's crazy to think that 10+ years later, I would actually be earning my PhD in Genetics. I will be the first in all my extended family to earn the title "Dr." #firstgenphd

(22) More broadly, this paper really shows that characterizing protein structures can help in illuminating the dark matter of genomes - we definitely need more structures of pathogen effectors to fully characterize the repertoire of important pathogens.

(21) In all, these results suggest that previous attempts at effector prediction in oomycetes may have missed out on many bona fide effectors, and that going forward new genome papers should incorporate the WY domain into their search strategy.
(20) (for the long story - please read the paper ;)

(19) With the help of many talented undergraduates, I cloned 21 of the WY effectors from lettuce downy mildew and did some functional characterization. Long story short, I found 3 that suppressed the lettuce immune system and I found 11 that were recognized by resistant lettuce.

(18) Most of this work was done in the first 5 weeks in the @michelmorelab. The next task was to go into the lab and prove that these predicted effectors actually acted like effectors. This task took about 4 years (!!!)

(17) I wanted to see if other downy mildews had WY proteins that didn't have an RXLR motif. I looked at downy mildews from grapevine, sunflower, tobacco, spinach, cucurbits, and Arabidopsis. And yes, they do have many WY proteins that don't have an RXLR (yellow+blue bars) https://t.co/ogYtv35hgp

(16) Here is a tree of the 59 proteins I found in the latest version of the genome. Similar proteins are clustered together. Red=signal peptide, black=RXLR, yellow=EER, blue=WY domains. https://t.co/hlDRVypVOX

(15) I used a model of this domain to see if I could find anything similar in the lettuce downy mildew genome. I found more than 50 proteins that seemed to share a similar sequence! And less than 20% of them had the RXLR motif.

(14) When I started my rotation, a few protein structures had recently been solved for Phytophthora effectors and they all had a common fold, termed the WY domain. Here is what it looks like at the protein and amino acid level (structure from https://t.co/CsjAZkFjmK) https://t.co/hXK2yZi3jF

(13) We tried looking for this signature in lettuce downy mildew, but didn't find very many proteins compared to other species. We began to suspect that downy mildew might be different from its cousins. So we tried to see if we could find other effector signatures.

(12) Downy mildews are related to Phytophthora species, which cause devastating plant diseases such as late blight of potato and sudden oak death. In Phytophthora, many effectors have a signature sequence called "RXLR" which you can use to fish out effectors from the genome.

(11) When I started in the lab as a rotation student, we had a pretty good draft genome and we wanted to start finding interesting genes - primarily, the ones encoding for effectors. So I taught myself a little computer programming (Unix and Perl) and got to work!
(10) The lettuce downy mildew genome paper can be found here! https://t.co/uoOH3DGQTl

(9) The @michelmorelab studies lettuce and the lettuce pathogen Bremia lactucae, which causes downy mildew. In order to better understand what genes the downy mildew is using to infect - and which ones might be detected in lettuce with resistance genes - we sequenced it's genome.

Journal editors: how common are R1 and R2? I don't tend to get those reviews for my papers, so I'm hoping these reviewers are the exception?! (8/8)

I'm sure my reviews could be improved (& shortened?). But I found enough wrong with the paper that I wrote ~2,000 words. I know peer-review is flawed, but how little respect are R1/R2 showing the scientific process by acting in this way? How do they think they are helping? (7/8)

There were 2 other reviewers. R1 recommended acceptance but didn't submit any comments. Nothing. R2 recommended major revisions but didn't spot any of the fundamental flaws (other than the missing PSA) and recommended no major changes. Their comments were <200 words. (6/8)

Also, transition probabilities were calculated incorrectly, and discounting was applied incorrectly. We all make mistakes, but these are quite big ones that should be picked up before submission. (5/8)
Now the bad. There was a one-way sensitivity analysis but no PSA. Who submits a Markov-modelling based CEA for publication without doing a PSA? Bizarre. (4/8)

First, the good. This was the first paper I have reviewed where I also got a copy of the model. This was really helpful. Without the model, I would have made more tentative points in a few instances; with the model I could be more definitive about potential/actual errors. (3/8)

This was not a good paper. It was fundamentally flawed in several ways (incorrect comparators, incorrect transition probabilities, errors in the model spreadsheet, limited consideration of uncertainty) and I recommended rejection (the editor agreed). (2/8)

I peer-reviewed a paper this past week and I have some thoughts. I'm not going to identify the journal, paper or authors, other than to say it was a Markov-model based CEA submitted to a #healtheconomics journal. (1/8)

You can see the happy numbers that collapse to one on the right and the 'unhappy' numbers that collapse to the 9 points on the left.

I started with 1000 random numbers between 1 and 100k, then I iterated through their 'happy' update. This resulted in a graph that I mapped to 2D with UMAP. I then animated by 'releasing' one number each frame and coloring it's trajectory in the graph.

Read a cool post about happy numbers by @evelynjlamb : https://t.co/TsBKpzZRB3 .You start with a number then square its digits, sum, and repeat, eventually reaching 1 (happy) or ending up in a 9 number loop. Once clusters have been identified, we attempt to find reliable genotypes in each cluster, using a presence/absence genotyping approach. Then we use a gram-schmidt orthogonalisation approach to try to identify a set of N distinguishing variants (for N clusters). https://t.co/frSqlv1VGL

The aim of the approach is to use genetic differences observable in pooled 3' scRNAseq data to distinguish samples, without genotypes. We use FreeBayes to find putative SNVs, then we build SNV by barcode allele count matrices, and use E-M to identify diff clusters https://t.co/BduItbCxc1

Many marine invertebrates such as sponges and tunicates appear to have distinctive consortia of bacteria living within them, but I'm being a bit of drone already.
A question I believe is still unanswered - though perhaps @currie_lab knows - is what insects do NOT have characteristic mutualisms with bacteria? What about other terrestrial invertebrates?

Not only social hymenoptera insects carry Actinomycetes - some solitary wasps - such as mud daubers that make nests like these - use them to protect their larvae https://t.co/2CJPu3y7M8 https://t.co/CbOEL36jvX

So ants invented gardens and pesticides long before we did. And the concept of a very precious heirloom. And they're not the only ones.  Some termites garden too - and yes, they also have specific associated Actinomycetes https://t.co/kkR8fvU9Ib https://t.co/CHfX0VXm9a

Remarkably, the three trees are congruent. This indicates that the ant-bacteria-fungus relationship originated once and the two microbes have  been passed on continuously in each ant lineage - a tripartite relationship stretching over 50 million years   https://t.co/7MTYHvkYrT

There are multiple species of ants which are leaf-cutting farmers.  Suppose you sequence markers from them and build a phylogenetic tree?  And from the fungi? And the actinomycetes? How do the trees compare?
As any gardener can tell you, let the weeds go and you'll soon lose your crops.  The ants carry Actinomycete bacteria that secrete compounds which specifically inhibit undesired fungal species
The ants don't eat the leaves - the ants cultivate in their nests gardens of fungi that grow on the leaves.  Which is the ultimate food source for the ants. https://t.co/CqivSQ6xKF
In the Americas live a number of ants which farm fungi - the leaf cutter ants. These ants cut large pieces of leaf and carry them to their colonies https://t.co/bI9wW6Kpiz

CG: Could S100b be a neuronal Zn buffer? Changes intracellular distribution of Zn. Zn is known to delay Ab42 aggregation and thus prevent removal of toxic oligomers by aggregation. Sub-stoichiometric S100b scavenges Zn and thus decrease toxic oligomer formation.

CG: Pro-inflammatory S100b cytokine. Generally intracellular, but with age gets secreted. Co-localizes with Ab42 fibrils. Monomeric Ab42 interacts with S100b at aggregation prone region of S100b. Complex of S100b and Ab42 studies by SAXS and NMR. https://t.co/pDojgUOsO7

ES: Catalysis is linked to (transient) dimerization and "interface stealing". When WT protein forms transient dimer, the mutant NTD becomes less stable, oxidized and then aggregate. Catalysis is combined effect of dimerization and redox transfer from WT to mutant. Case closed.

ES: But, wait, there's more. What happens if we add GSSG then catalysis should disappear. It doesn't. It's not enough just to be oxidizing. N-domain unfolding of mutant is more rapid when catalyst is present: WT promotes conformational change in mutant crystallin

If you want to do genetics, do genetics; leave ethnicity/race at the door. If you want to study sociology and society - race/ethnicity is a complex part of your study (and v.complex), predominantly cultural, and don't mistake it for genetics.

These biases and complications - ranging from full blown discrimination and the awful history of racism, and other complex things - what does "Irish Traveller" as an "ethnicity" really mean - are worth studying but rarely useful to understand the biology of humans

Science lives and operates in society, and we have a complex, historically messy, culturally screwed up thing called "race/ethnicity". These ideas are everywhere but they are not just "not useful" in genetics, they have strange, you-dont-want-to-use them biases

Basically if you use self reported ethnicity to subset or (worse still!) as a covariate, you have no idea what other confounders you are bringing into your analysis, and you are going to ask your PC genetic modelling to do even more! Why do it? Don't do it!

Arguably this is even worse in the US "European American" population which has both Native American and African haplotypes coming in at some rate *and* complex hetreogeneity of European founding also non random in geography (Finns in Seattle; Germans in Philidelphia etc)
(I get quickly lost in the population history of Europea and anywhere else though I find it fascinating - @aylwyn_scally is my go to source for the latest and greatest on this)
But.... if I had mainly Sardinians in my study, this would all flip around, and all the other Europeans would look "odd". It's all about how you sample people.

Sardinians are overrepresented in Anatolian ur-Farmer genetics vs your "run-of-the-mill" Flemish/French/South British/Rhinelander blend of Anatolian Farmer + Beaker People + some early Hunter Gatherer

This study is very valuable and important for me not only because of the topic, analyses etc. but also because it is the first article that I am the last author. I want to thank Ulas, because he made this process so easy and enjoyable.

Overall: 1) the increase in heterogeneity is not a process that operates over time but is specific to the aging period, 2) gene regulation might be an underlying mechanism, 3) increase in heterogeneity is important in aging-related functions & may have functional outcome

We showed these genes are related to biological pathways related to aging and cognitive decline. Then, we asked "What may cause this heterogeneity?" and analyzed TFs and miRNAs. Apart from specific factors being related, we found the total # of regulators could be a factor.

We examined a large number of brain regions and the expression heterogeneity in 0-20 yo (development) vs. 20+ years (aging). We did not observe a consistent change in development, but we see certain genes became consistently more variable with age during aging.

This should be the major advantage of using #NGLess as a basis: the tool should waste less of the user's time. For us, this means (1) fast and good error messages, (2) handling all the nitty gritty (eg, compressing/decompressing files) automatically,...
Our tool is faster than the alternatives in computational time, but we also wanted to save bioinformatician time. https://t.co/hzwM6evaH9
The overall concept (build gene catalog, annotate it, then use it to profile samples) is well tested and can produce fast and robust results (in the manuscript, we show this with simulated data).
These profiler are available for human gut, mouse gut, pig gut, dog gut, and marine samples. They are based on pre-built, pre-annotated gene catalogs that are also part of the manuscript.

We propose a set of predefined pipelines (profiles) that are easy to use (just pass in a path to input and one to output) and should work out of the box. But we knew that they would never cover all cases, so they are very easy to adapt and customize.

We wanted standardized, easy-to-use, 1-click install-and-run pipelines, that are reproducible, but also that they be flexible and extensible.Our proposal is to do these pipelines with #NGLess, a special language we developed for this project.
tl;dr we present profiling tools for metagenomes.Give them a metagenome, get a table of measurements out. These measurements are both taxonomic and functional.
